"Mander Ü., Uuemaa E., Kull A., Kanal A., Maddison M., Soosaar K., Salm J.-O., Lesta M., Hansen R., Kuller R., Harding A., Augustin J.","Assessment of methane and nitrous oxide fluxes in rural landscapes",2010,"Landscape and Urban Planning","98","3-4",,"172","181",,,10.1016/j.landurbplan.2010.08.021,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-78049231302&partnerID=40&md5=01ab1c39438cf96f8a38c9e8c59c36e0","Department of Geography, Institute of Ecology and Earth Sciences, University of Tartu, Estonia; Keelion Translations OÜ, Tartu, Estonia; Institute of Landscape Matter Dynamics, Leibniz Centre for Agricultural Landscape Research (ZALF), Müncheberg, Germany","Mander, Ü., Department of Geography, Institute of Ecology and Earth Sciences, University of Tartu, Estonia; Uuemaa, E., Department of Geography, Institute of Ecology and Earth Sciences, University of Tartu, Estonia; Kull, A., Department of Geography, Institute of Ecology and Earth Sciences, University of Tartu, Estonia; Kanal, A., Department of Geography, Institute of Ecology and Earth Sciences, University of Tartu, Estonia; Maddison, M., Department of Geography, Institute of Ecology and Earth Sciences, University of Tartu, Estonia; Soosaar, K., Department of Geography, Institute of Ecology and Earth Sciences, University of Tartu, Estonia; Salm, J.-O., Department of Geography, Institute of Ecology and Earth Sciences, University of Tartu, Estonia; Lesta, M., Department of Geography, Institute of Ecology and Earth Sciences, University of Tartu, Estonia; Hansen, R., Department of Geography, Institute of Ecology and Earth Sciences, University of Tartu, Estonia; Kuller, R., Department of Geography, Institute of Ecology and Earth Sciences, University of Tartu, Estonia; Harding, A., Department of Geography, Institute of Ecology and Earth Sciences, University of Tartu, Estonia, Keelion Translations OÜ, Tartu, Estonia; Augustin, J., Institute of Landscape Matter Dynamics, Leibniz Centre for Agricultural Landscape Research (ZALF), Müncheberg, Germany","We estimated CH4 and N2O emissions from the main land-use types in rural landscapes using data from the literature (950 study sites/experiments from the temperate and boreal zone published from 1980 to 2009 in 165 scientific papers indexed by the ISI Web of Science) and assessed the emission potential of CH4 and N2O from rural landscapes in Estonia. According to this analysis, natural peatlands and marshes appeared to be the most important CH4 emitters, whereas N2O is emitted mainly from drained peatlands and marshes, set aside areas, conventional arable lands, fertilized grasslands, and coniferous and mixed forests - all on hydromorphic soils. The estimated median value of annual CH4-C and N2O-N fluxes for Estonian rural landscapes are 25,519 and 11,050t respectively. CH4 consumption makes up 13.2% of the emission. The largest CH4 emitters are peatlands (17,746tCH4-Cyear-1; 60%), whereas coniferous and mixed forests on hydromorphic soils with altered hydrologic regime are responsible for the bulk (51%) of N2O fluxes. The Global Warming Potential (GWP) of Estonian rural land-use types (42,685km2) from potential CH4 and N2O fluxes is 5.99 million t of CO2 equivalents, of which N2O is responsible for 86%. Several measures for the further mitigation of greenhouse gas emission from rural landscapes are proposed. © 2010 Elsevier B.V.","Automorphic soils; CH4; Global Warming Potential; Hydromorphic soils; Land cover; N2O","Automorphic soils; CH<sub>4</sub>; Global Warming Potential; Hydromorphic soils; Land cover; N<sub>2</sub>O; Forestry; Gas emissions; Global warming; Greenhouse gases; Land use; Methane; Nitrogen oxides; Wetlands; Soils; arable land; coniferous forest; grassland; greenhouse gas; hydrological regime; land cover; literature review; marsh; methane; mixed forest; nitrous oxide; peatland; rural landscape; temperate environment; Emission; Estonia; Forestry; Gas; Greenhouse Gases; Land Use; Methane; Nitrogen Oxides; Soil; Wetlands; Estonia",,,,,,"Albrecht, A., Kandji, S.T., Carbon sequestration in tropical agroforestry systems (2003) Agric. Ecosyst. Environ., 99, pp. 15-27; Allen, D.E., Mendham, D.S., Bhupinderpal-Singh, Cowie, A., Wang, W., Dalal, R.C., Raison, R.J., Nitrous oxide and methane emissions from soil are reduced following afforestation of pasture lands in three contrasting climatic zones (2009) Aust. J. Soil Res., 47, pp. 443-458; Alm, J., Shurpali, N.J., Minkkinen, K., Aro, L., Hytönen, J., Laurila, T., Lohila, A., Laine, J., Emission factors and their uncertainty for the exchange of CO2, CH4 and N2O in Finnish managed peatlands (2007) Boreal Environ. Res., 12, pp. 191-209; Ambus, P., Zechmeister-Boltenstern, S., Butterbach-Bahl, K., Sources of nitrous oxide emitted from European forest soils (2006) Biogeosciences, 3, pp. 135-145; Aurela, M., Laurila, T., Tuovinen, J.P., Annual CO2 balance of a subarctic fen in northern Europe: importance of the wintertime efflux (2002) J. Geophys. Res. Atmos., 107 (D21), p. 4607; Bailey, N., Lee, J.T., Thompson, S., Maximising the natural capital benefits of habitat creation: spatially targeting native woodland using GIS (2006) Landscape Urban Plann., 75, pp. 227-243; Bareth, G., Heincke, M., Glatzel, S., Soil-land-use-system approach to estimate nitrous oxide emissions from agricultural soils (2001) Nutr. Cycl. Agroecosys., 60, pp. 219-234; Bernoux, M., Branca, G., Carro, A., Lipper, L., Smith, G., Bockel, L., Ex-ante greenhouse gas balance of agriculture and forestry development programs (2010) Sci. Agricola, 67 (1), pp. 31-40; Booth, M.S., Stark, J.M., Hart, S.C., Soil-mixing effects on inorganic nitrogen production and consumption in forest and shrubland soils (2006) Plant Soil, 289, pp. 5-15; Bridgham, S.D., Megonigal, J.P., Keller, J.K., Bliss, N.B., Trettin, C., The carbon balance of North American wetlands (2006) Wetlands, 26, pp. 889-916; Burton, D.L., Li, X., Grant, C.A., Influence of fertilizer nitrogen source and manageme